 Description:
 This line item funds modifications to the UH-1Y and AH-1Z aircraft and related systems, collectively referred to as H-1 aircraft. H-1s belong to the same unit, Marine Light Attack Helicopter Squadrons (HMLA),
 and are often flown together for complementary mission roles. The mission of the HMLA is to support the combatant commander by providing offensive air support, utility support, armed escort, and airborne
 supporting arms coordination day or night under all weather conditions during expeditionary, joint or combined operations. H-1s are capable of offensive air support (to include Counter Unmanned Aerial System
 (CUAS) and Counter Maritime), armed escort, armed/visual reconnaissance, and airborne supporting arms coordination. The UH-1Y utility helicopter is further capable of conducting combat assault transport,
 airborne command and control, casualty evacuation and special operations support. The UH-1Y is crewed by two pilots and two crew chiefs with maximum capacity of 12 personnel. The AH-1Z attack helicopter
 is the Marine Corps primary provider of air to surface fires; capable of providing volume of fires support for anti-armor, counter maritime, precision strike, CUAS, and anti-helicopter and point air defense via
 armament including the Sidewinder and Hellfire missiles, Joint Air-to-Ground Missile (JAGM), Advanced Precision Kill Weapon System (APKWS), Precision Attack Strike Munition (PASM), a chin-mounted 20mm
 turret, and a wide variety of forward-firing and external stores. The AH-1Z is a tandem, two-seat attack helicopter crewed by two pilots.

 The final domestic aircraft were delivered in September 2022 and are expected to fly into the 2050s until a replacement platform is developed and selected. The Marine Corps prioritized and invested in a H-1
 Mid-Life Modernization strategy in order to cover fires gaps and bridge to an eventual replacement program. Funding for modifications is a culmination of the planned mid-life modernization strategy and aligns
 with the Marine Corps' top three H-1 priorities of lethality, Digital Interoperability (DI), and improved survivability, while enabling future capability improvements, addressing obsolescence, and improving reliability.
 Modifications also improve readiness, increase aircraft availability, and decrease operating costs. Reliability improvements and obsolescence management will reduce flight hour costs, maintain/increase
 operational capability, and increase time on wing. Improvements include software upgrades and integration test assets to support engineering modifications.

 OSIP 15-12: Incorporates modifications to increase H-1 aircraft and aircrew's Digital Interoperability (DI) and survivability on the battlefield. DI Link-16 provides Maritime Multi-Domain awareness, acting as a
 kill-web enabler and effector that shortens the kill chain and improves battlefield intelligence sharing. Terrain Awareness Warning System (TAWS) modification brings terrain and obstacle warning capability to
 the existing Ground Proximity Warning System (GPWS). Health and Usage Monitoring System (HUMS) modification provides early detection and improved diagnosis of system degradation, component failure
 and abnormal operating system; and resolves obsolescence issues, aids in maintenance forecasting, resulting in long-term cost savings and increased readiness. Cryptographic Modernization (CM) modernizes
 the H-1's avionic cryptographic systems in accordance with National Security Agency (NSA) mandates, transitioning them to a post-quantum resistant state. Improvements leverage common architectures and
 existing technology to minimize modification costs, procurement costs, and fielding time.

 OSIP 16-12: Incorporates changes to the AH-1Z and UH-1Y to increase the Lethality and Survivability of both platforms as directed by HQMC. Lethality will be increased on the AH-1Z by replacing the obsolete
 AIM-9M air-to-air missile with the AIM-9X, which is a significantly more effective weapon system. Additionally, modifications will be made to weapons stations 1 & 6 of the AH-1Z that will allow carriage of both


