 Description:
 This line item funds modifications to a group of trainer aircraft systems which includes the US Navy Test Pilot School (USNTPS) aircraft, the TH-73A, and the T-54.

 Test Pilot School aircraft support training of test pilots, Naval Flight Officers (NFOs), Flight Test and System Test Engineers. TPS aircraft include (10) T-38C, (10) TH-57B/C, (5) UH-72A, (6) OH-58C, (2) U-6A,
 (1) NU-1B, (2) X-26, (2) UV-18A , and (1) C-26A. Efforts include modifications to airframe, avionics, power/propulsion and sub-systems, necessary to address safety, reliability, maintainability, obsolescence,
 capability, system/sub-system components, and Diminishing Manufacturing Sources and Material Shortages (DMSMS) requirements. Modifications, particularly to avionic systems, may also be driven by new
 Cyber Security requirements.

 The TH-73A is a single engine, multi-seat rotary wing aircraft. The TH-73A replaces the TH-57 to provide rotary wing training to the fleet. Modifications address correction of deficiency issues that arise on aircraft
 accepted off the production line as well as safety issues. Total TH-73A inventory is 130.

 The T-54 is a twin-engine, multi-seat turboprop aircraft produced by Textron Aviation Incorporated and is utilized to provide multi-engine training to student pilots. Specifically, this aircraft provides pipeline training
 for the P-8,
 EP-3, KC-130, E-6, E-2, MV-22 and CMV-22. Current Navy inventory is 63 aircraft.




