 Description:
 (OSIP 14-90) AN/APR-39 RWR

 DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION:
 The AN/APR-39 family of Radar Signal Detecting Systems (RSDS) is designed for United States Marine Corps (USMC), United States Navy (USN), United States Air Force (USAF), and United States Army
 assault support aircraft. It provides onboard situational awareness and warnings of radar Radio Frequency (RF) threats. The system requirements are governed by the Operational Requirements Document
 (ORD) number 545-88-00, dated February 14, 2000. The AN/APR-39 serves as the platform bus controller for multiple Missile Warning Systems (MWS), including the AN/AAQ-24, AN/AAQ-45, AN/AAR-47, AN/
 AAR-59, and AN/AAR-61. Additionally, it provides chaff dispense commands to the AN/ALE-47 Countermeasures Dispenser System (CMDS). The system consists of a processor, quadrant antennas, a low-band
 array antenna, a cockpit control unit (legacy configuration) or glass cockpit integration (modern configuration), and two to four receivers, depending on the aircraft configuration.

 This OSIP supports Engineering Change Proposals (ECPs), hardware/software upgrades, and modernization efforts, including Radar Warning Receiver and Radar Frequency Countermeasures enhancements. It
 also facilitates integration with emerging aircraft survivability equipment enablers. The program integrates hardware and software solutions that link onboard Integrated Aircraft Survivability Equipment (iASE) with
 mission planning and information systems. iASE includes RF, Infrared (IR), and Laser Warning (LW) sensors, as well as CMDS and expendables. Furthermore, the system has the capability to store RF sensor
 data for post-mission threat analysis. Updates are required through the Future Year Defense Program (FYDP) for various platforms. This program addresses deficiencies in AN/APR-39 variants by improving
 Direction of Arrival accuracy, resolving time-delayed detection issues, and enhancing threat identification. These improvements significantly enhance situational awareness for combat aircrews operating in
 saturated RF environments. Additionally, the program resolves reliability and maintainability issues that persist in legacy systems. The AN/APR-39 family of systems is installed on the following USMC and USN
 assault support aircraft: V-22, H-1, H-60, H-53, and C-130.

 DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES: The AN/APR-39 is in the production and sustainment phase (MSIII3Q/96). The DoN is the lead service with Army interest. This budget
 supports integration, validation/verification and procurement of the upgraded APR-39 system.




