 Description:
 The F-35 Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) Program will develop and deploy a family of highly common, affordable, next generation, stealthy, multi-role strike fighters that meet the needs of multiple services and
 countries. The United States Marine Corps Short Take Off and Vertical Landing (STOVL) Operational Safety Improvement Program provides near and long-term improvements to the fleet, focusing on
 documented deficiencies related to safety, reliability and maintainability, aircraft systems, avionics, and Block upgrades. These modifications and selected component changes are being accomplished by
 contractor field teams and organic depot retrofit activities.

 Block 4 upgrades provide a more robust performance in navigation, weapons, avionics, survivability, maneuverability, maintainability, and mission deployment of the F-35B platform. This modification program will
 bring early production Low-Rate Initial Production (LRIP) aircraft and integrated systems to a common fleet configuration as fielded capabilities evolve over the course of the F-35B program.

 To meet emerging deficiencies, the airframe and integrated systems must be modified as critical corrections/changes are identified. Funds will be used to manage, prepare, process, and incorporate changes
 to sustain and improve F-35B system operations. The Structural Life Limit Parts (SLLP) Program is the preponderance of the correction of deficiencies effort. The Structural Life Limit Parts (SLLP) Program will
 remove life limits below 8,000 hours. In FY2027, the Program will conduct Non-Recurring engineering (NRE) as well as procure and install SLLP modifications.

 The FY 2027 request for F-35B Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) includes $428,881 thousand of discretionary and $81,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $509,881 thousand. The discretionary
 funds provide for Correction of Deficiency, Block 4, APG-85 Radar, Propulsion, and Reliability & Maintainability modification and retrofit products. The mandatory funds provide for Block 4 modification and retrofit
 products.

 DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES:

 The seven dock expansion at Fleet Readiness Center East will be fully activated in FY2027 which will increase the capacity for installations.




