 Description:
 The F-35 Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) Program will develop and deploy a family of highly common, affordable, next generation, stealthy, multi-role strike fighters that meet the needs of multiple services and
 countries. The United States Navy Carrier Variant (CV) Modifications Program provides near and long-term improvements to the fleet, focusing on documented deficiencies related to safety, reliability and
 maintainability, avionics, block upgrades, and aircraft systems. These modifications and selected component changes are being accomplished by contractor field teams and organic depot retrofit activities.

 Block 4 upgrades provide more robust performance in navigation, weapons, avionics, survivability, maneuverability, maintainability, and mission deployment of the F-35C platform. This modification program will
 bring early production Low-Rate Initial Production (LRIP) aircraft and integrated systems to a common fleet configuration as fielded capabilities evolve over the course of the F-35C program.

 In order to meet emerging deficiencies, the airframe and integrated systems must be modified as critical corrections/changes are identified. Funds will be used to manage, prepare, process and incorporate
 changes to sustain and improve F-35C system operations. The Structural Life Limit Parts (SLLP) Program is the preponderance of the correction of deficiencies effort. The SLLP modification effort will remove life
 limits below 8,000 hours. In FY2027, the Program will conduct Non-Recurring engineering (NRE) as well as procure and install SLLP modifications.

 Under the SLLP Program, the F-35C has a unique set of life limiting structural deficiencies under the upper wing skin referred to as the CV Upper Wing Skin (UWS) effort. Early LRIP aircraft have ~29 of these
 deficiencies which decrease in subsequent LRIP and LOT aircraft as corrections get made in production aircraft. The Program plans to correct all these deficiencies during a single depot induction to eliminate
 the need to remove the wing skin more than once. The first of these inductions are planned for FY26 to prove out the modification kits, installation tooling, and instructions. In FY2027, the program will continue
 to procure and install other SLLP modifications.

 The FY 2027 request for F-35C Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) includes $135,612 thousand of discretionary and $81,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $216,612 thousand. The discretionary
 funds provide for Correction of Deficiency, Block 4, APG-85 Radar, Propulsion, and Reliability & Maintainability modification and retrofit products. The mandatory funds provide for Correction of Deficiency and
 Block 4 modification and retrofit products.

 DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES:
 The Program will induct its first aircraft for the CV Upper Wing Skin set of 29 SLLP modifications in FY2027.




