INSERT INTO public.procurement_line_years (line_id, fiscal_year, service, appropriation, appr_code, ba, line_number, title, quantity, unit_cost, prior_year_actual, current_year_enacted, request_amount, fydp_yr1, fydp_yr2, fydp_yr3, fydp_yr4, narrative, content_hash, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$PROC_NAVY_NA_L0058$$, 2027, $$Navy$$, $$PROC_NAVY$$, $$NAVY$$, NULL, $$58$$, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, $$ set may not be exact or sum exactly due to rounding.

 Justification:
 Aviation sparing is a critical enabler of naval power projection. It directly supports the Chief of Naval Operations (CNO) and the Commandant of the Marine Corps (CMC) in building and sustaining a credible
 combat force capable of keeping sea lanes open, deterring conflict, and winning wars. By delivering initial plane-side spare and repair parts per authorized allowance listings, aviation sparing ensures the
 operational readiness of naval aviation platforms for force generation and global deployment across key theaters like EUCOM and INDOPACOM. Without timely and sufficient aviation sparing, the Navy and
 Marine Corps (DoN) risk degraded readiness, delayed response times, and reduced combat effectiveness in contested environments.

 FY2027 funding levels prioritize immediate readiness needs across the fleet, ensuring sustained support for today's afloat deployers, shore stations, and expeditionary units. At the same time, this investment
 strategically supports the long-term sustainment of key aviation platforms and systems critical to the Airwing of the Future and the Aviation Combat Element (ACE).

 Due to multi-year supplier lead times, the DoN must invest in spares today to ensure future readiness and operational success. These strategic investments increase the range and depth of spares onboard
 CVNs and the ACE, directly improving deployed aviation readiness and supporting the CNO's 90-day endurance requirement for repair parts. Enhancing onboard spares also extends CVN and the ACE time on
 station without resupply, reducing the logistics burden in contested environments.

 Initial contractor spares, engine spares, and Peculiar Support Equipment (PSE) spares are major cost drivers as new T/M/S continue to be introduced, procured, and modified for technological improvements.
 Aviation spares support changes to basing plans and required support packages. More specifically, AVCAL/SHORCAL funding enables maximized employment for Carrier Air Wings/Marine Aircraft Group
 squadrons to train and deploy with minimal Non-Mission Capable, Supply (NMCS) impacts to readiness. The aviation spares budget further supports the Secretary of Defense's strategy to improve warfighting
 readiness by addressing urgent warfighting materiel readiness shortfalls.

 Initial Spares:

 FY2027 Initial spares funding includes required support of the following aircraft platforms:

 F/A-18 E/F (0145)

 FY2027 funding supports Consolidated Automated Support System (CASS) Operational Test Program Sets (OTPS) for the Infrared Search and Track (IRST) System. This funding supports EO4 emerging system
 requirements to support F/A-18E/F IRST AN/ASG-34 Block III Upgrade and hardware obsolescence of CASS/eCASS EO3 configuration.

 Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) Carrier Variant (CV) (F-35C) (0147) and Short Takeoff and Vertical Landing (STOVL) (F-35B) (0152)

 CV Funding increased from $202.029M (FY2026) to $520.056M (FY2027) (+$318.027M)

 The FY2027 request for Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) Carrier Variant (CV) (F-35C) USN includes $422.842 million of discretionary and $0 of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $422.842 million.

