 Description:
 AN/SLQ-32: Provides surface combatants defensive and offensive electronic warfare capabilities that are critical to ship-based layered defense.

 Defensive systems provide Electronic Support (ES) capability- searching for, identifying, and tracking sources of electromagnetic (EM) energy for the purpose of immediate threat recognition, targeting, planning,
 and conducting of future operations. ES systems complement other ship-based sensors and contribute to a surface combatant's overall picture of its threat environment.

 Offensive systems provide Electronic Attack (EA) capability- directing EM energy to defeat enemy fires. This non-kinetic soft-kill capability broadens ship self-defense options, deepens magazines, provides
 reduced logistics, and lowers "cost-per-shot" compared to kinetic munitions.

 AN/SLQ-32(V) is the core of surface electronic warfare (EW) capability. Navy has fielded surface electronic warfare systems designated as AN/SLQ-32(V)1-7. AN/SLQ-32(V)1-5 are legacy systems no longer in
 production. AN/SLQ-32(V)6 is an ES system currently in production. AN/SLQ-32(V)7, which builds on (V)6, is also in production, and it provides offensive EA at the strike group level. Scaled Onboard Electronic
 Attack (SOEA) is a future capability currently in development that will provide EA self-protection capability to ships unable to support AN/SLQ-32(V)7 due to size, weight, power, and cooling.

 The Surface Electronic Warfare Improvement Program (SEWIP) provides progressively greater capability through a series of block upgrades to AN/SLQ-32(V) systems:
 - SEWIP Block 1 provided federated Specific Emitter Identification (SEI), an upgraded console and display, and High-Gain
 High-Sensitivity (HGHS). (Navy recently divested of these requirements for higher priorities ).
 - SEWIP Block 2 provides enhanced Electronic Support (ES). Block 2 Lite provides ES to ships unable to support Block 2 due
 to size, weight, power, and cooling constraints.
 - SEWIP Block 3 provides Electronic Attack (EA) capability.

 Signal Processing Upgrade was previously referred to as VPX Tech Refresh. Updating the name to better describe full capability being delivered with the upgrade to the below deck equipment.

 Since the FY26 budget request, (V)6 VPX Upgrade Engineering Change Proposal (ECP) has been renamed AN/SLQ-32(V) Signal Processing Upgrade to more accurately describe full capability being
 delivered with the upgrade to the below deck equipment. The Signal Processing Upgrade is the below deck computing power behind surface EW capabilities. The Signal Processor upgrade integrates above
 deck hardware components with each other and the combat system. Signal Processing Upgrades are critical enablers of the added capabilities delivered by SEWIP block upgrades and next-generation


LI 2312 - AN/SLQ-32                                                                                     UNCLASSIFIED
