 Description:
 Funding for LI 2900 Maritime Integrated Broadcast Service (MIBS) has been realigned into LI 2361 Automatic Identification System (AIS) as part of Other Procurement, Navy Line Item-Consolidation starting
 in FY 2026. This effort consolidates the existing number of PEs/BLIs identified by BSOs and FMB to group technology projects to allow flexibility that would foster innovation and promote efficiency. PE/BLI
 consolidation meets the DoW Implementation Plan from the Commission on PPBE Interim Report.

 1U030: AIS is required for safety of navigation for all surface ships and submarines. AIS is a maritime Very High Frequency (VHF) communication system, which allows ships to exchange navigation, ship
 identification, and cargo information machine-to-machine via VHF transponders. AIS provides vessels with the ability to rapidly identify and track commercial shipping, which significantly increases the Navy's
 ability to distinguish between normal and suspicious merchant ships headed towards United States and allied ports around the globe. AIS provides critical track data to the Common Operational Picture (COP)
 on surface ships, AN/BYG-1 Combat System on submarines, Global Command and Control System-Maritime (GCCS-M) on Force Level ships, and Global Command and Control System-Joint (GCCS-J) at Fleet
 Maritime Operations Centers (MOC). The AIS submarine configuration provides an interface to the AN/BYG-1 Combat System and encrypted AIS capability. This capability dramatically improves the Combatant
 Commanders' situational awareness and Maritime Domain Awareness (MDA) data sharing capabilities in support of regional engagement and tracking efforts against potential maritime terrorism threats.

 Funds will be used to continue the initial fielding of AIS (V)9 Program of Record systems, their follow-on cyber hardening upgrades, as well as the continuation of surface ship cyber hardening. The AIS submarine
 variant consists of a combination of government/commercial software, AIS power and navigation subsystem, AIS antenna selector switch, AIS antenna interface unit, AIS data distribution laptop, and AIS terminal
 data processing unit. The need for AIS systems is especially important for submarines, which have limited maneuverability. The AIS (V)3 and (V)9 Submarine configuration provides situational awareness (to
 include encrypted AIS message traffic from United States Coast Guard vessels) during time-constrained ascents to communications depth, thereby significantly reducing the risk of a collision.

 In order to address potential vulnerabilities identified by the Naval Cyber Warfare Development Group (NCWDG) and in compliance with the "Expression of Cyber Requirement for Automatic Identification
 System" dated 31 Jan 2017, a cybersecurity engineering change will be implemented on all AIS systems in order to protect downstream systems from malformed or anomalous AIS data. Funds are being used
 to procure and install a new Warship AIS compliant transponder and AIS Terminal Box on all AIS (V)1 equipped surface ships. A new small form factor AIS workstation will be procured and installed on Force-
 Level ships equipped with AIS (V)2 systems. This has already been installed at Fleet HQ MOCs equipped with AIS (V)5 systems. New AIS laptops and Warship AIS compatible transponders will be procured and
 installed on all submarines equipped with an AIS (V)3 or AIS (V)9 Program of Record system. The above hardware configuration changes are required to implement software and firmware modifications that will
 detect, log, and filter all incoming AIS data from unverified sources, alert operators to the presence of anomalous AIS data and protect systems and users of AIS data downstream from the data collection point.
 These users include GCCS-M, GCCS-J, Distributed Common Ground System - Navy (DCGS-N), Electronic Chart Display and Information System - Navy (ECDIS-N), BYG-1, and others.



